Hereâ€™s the **clean start** process for Debian/Parrot OS:

---

## **1. Stop and disable the service**

```bash
sudo systemctl stop twingate
sudo systemctl disable twingate
```

---

## **2. Remove all Twingate packages**

```bash
sudo apt purge -y twingate twingate-latest
```

---

## **3. Delete leftover data and configs**

```bash
sudo rm -rf /var/lib/twingate
sudo rm -rf /etc/twingate
sudo rm -rf /usr/share/keyrings/twingate-client-keyring.gpg
sudo rm -f /etc/apt/sources.list.d/twingate.list
```

---

## **4. Update package list**

```bash
sudo apt update
```

---

## **5. Reinstall from scratch**

```bash
curl -fsSL https://packages.twingate.com/apt/gpg.key | sudo gpg --dearmor -o /usr/share/keyrings/twingate-client-keyring.gpg
echo "deb [signed-by=/usr/share/keyrings/twingate-client-keyring.gpg] https://packages.twingate.com/apt/ * *" | sudo tee /etc/apt/sources.list.d/twingate.list
sudo apt update
sudo apt install twingate
```

---

## **6. Set correct permissions (to prevent last issue)**

```bash
sudo chown -R root:root /var/lib/twingate
sudo chmod -R 755 /var/lib/twingate
```

---

## **7. Run setup again**

```bash
sudo twingate setup
```

Enter your Twingate network name and finish the authentication.

---

## **8. Start the service**

```bash
sudo systemctl enable twingate
sudo systemctl start twingate
```

Check:

```bash
twingate status
